{"title_page": "Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi", "text_new": "{{short description|American-Japanese television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi\n| image                    = Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi.svg\n| image_size               = 220px\n| genre                    = <!--Must be sourced per Template:Infobox television-->\n| creator                  = Sam Register\n| director                 = {{unbulleted list|Darin McGowan|Howie Perry|Scott O'Brien|[[Darrell Van Citters]] <small>(supervising director)</small>}}\n| starring                 = {{unbulleted list|[[Ami Onuki]]|[[Yumi Yoshimura]]}}\n| voices                   = {{unbulleted list|[[Janice Kawaye]]|[[Grey DeLisle]]|[[Keone Young]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Puffy AmiYumi]]<br />[[Andy Sturmer]]\n| opentheme                = \"[[Hi Hi (Puffy AmiYumi)|Hi Hi]]\"<br /><small>performed by [[Puffy AmiYumi]]</small>\n| endtheme                 = \"Hi Hi\" <small>(Instrumental)</small>\n| composer                 = {{unbulleted list|Puffy AmiYumi <small>(original songs)</small>|[[Andy Sturmer]]}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| network                  = [[Cartoon Network]]\n| executive_producer       = Sam Register<br />Tramm Wigzell\n| producer                 = Ashley Postlewaite\n| editor                   = {{unbulleted list|Thom Whitehead <br /><small>(Season 1)</small>|Joe Campana|Nate Pacheco <small>(Season 1\u20132)</small>|Michael D'Ambrosio|Rick Greenwald <br /><small>(Season 2\u20133)</small>|Michelle Wong <br /><small>(Season 4)}}\n| company                  = [[Renegade Animation]]<br />[[Cartoon Network Studios]]\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| num_seasons              = 3\n| num_episodes             = 39 (117 segments and 1 pilot)\n| list_episodes            = List of Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi episodes\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_run                = April 22, 2003 {{small|(pilot)}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2004|11|19}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2006|6|27}}\n| website                  = \n}}\n'''''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi''''' is an American animated television series created by [[Sam Register]] for [[Cartoon Network]].<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=284-285}}</ref> Produced by [[Renegade Animation]] and [[Cartoon Network Studios]], the series stars fictionalized and animated versions of the [[Music of Japan|Japanese]] [[pop rock]] group [[Puffy AmiYumi]]. The series premiered on November 19, 2004 and ended on June 27, 2006 with a total of three seasons and 39 episodes, leaving a total of 34 episodes aired and five episodes unaired in North America.\n\nDuring its run, the series has been nominated for an [[Annie Award]] three times. The series has developed a strong [[cult following]]. Merchandise based on the series has also been produced during its run, such as video games, home media releases, toys, and clothing.\n\n==Premise==\n[[File:Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi Characters.png|220px|thumb|left|The main cast of the show. From left to right: Ami, Kaz, Yumi, Jang-Keng, and Tekirai.]]\n''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' follows the adventures of two [[pop stars]] and best friends: [[Yumi Yoshimura]] ([[Grey DeLisle]]), a cynical, sarcastic, rough and tough [[punk rock]]er; and [[Ami Onuki]] ([[Janice Kawaye]]), a peppy, optimistic and cute schoolgirl. Both are based off the real Japanese [[Pop music|pop]] duo [[Puffy AmiYumi]], but with different appearances and exaggerated personalities. They travel around the world on their customized tour bus along with their well-intentioned yet greedy manager Kaz Harada ([[Keone Young]]). From rocking out at a concert to hanging out in their hometown of [[Tokyo, Japan|Tokyo]], the duo take the world by storm with their musical talent, trend-setting style, and humor, dishing out lessons in J-pop justice and establishing the international language of \"cool\" along the way.\n\nSecondary characters include: Jang-Keng (Grey DeLisle) and Tekirai (Janice Kawaye), the duo's pet cats who enjoy tormenting Kaz; Harmony ([[Sandy Fox]]), a six-year-old girl who is the self-proclaimed \"Number One Fan\" of Puffy AmiYumi and (later) Kaz and constantly stalks them; Eldwin Blair (Nathan Carlson), a sinister land developer who tries to tear down beloved places for his own selfish needs; King Chad ([[Katie Leigh]]), a selfish \"bad boy\" who is a master of the card game ''Stu-Pi-Doh!'' (a parody of ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh!]]''); the evil Talent Suckers (Nathan Carlson; [[Corey Burton]]), a [[vampire]] rock trio from [[Transylvania]]; and Atchan ([[Rob Paulsen]]), a caricature of Vo Atsushi (lead singer of the [[Pop music|pop]] band New Rote'ka) who speaks in third-person and thinks he is a superhero.\n\nThe animated Puffy AmiYumi travel all over the world in their tour bus. While appearing the same size as a regular bus on the outside, it appears to have enough internal space to house the girls' rooms (including full-sized beds), Kaz's room, their equipment, televisions, and computers, among other things. In the episode \"Domo\", Kaz refers to an upstairs area. It also seems capable of running on autopilot, as Kaz, Ami, and Yumi are sometimes sitting in the rear cabin of the bus while traveling. Occasionally, the rear door has been opened to receive packages delivered by a boy on a scooter.\n\nDuring the first season, the show included [[live-action]] clips of the real Ami and Yumi making childish commentary (in English and non-subtitled Japanese) at the beginning and end of each episode. They only performed short clips at the beginning of the show during the second and third seasons. Starting with the second season, the duo was sometimes shown holding title cards introducing the cartoon segments. At the end of the episode \"Sitcomi Yumi\", Ami and Yumi watched television and saw the animated Kaz with the real Ami and Yumi. All of the live-action clips were produced by Freegate, Ltd.\n\nThe real PUFFY performs the cartoon's theme song (which is also in Japanese, German, European French, Canadian French, Castilian Spanish, Latin American Spanish, Danish, Norwegian, Polish, Chinese, Taiwanese Mandarin, Dutch, Arabic, Hebrew, Turkish, Brazilian Portuguese and European Portuguese in the respective regions), and many episodes feature one or more of the duo's songs playing in the background, along with music by [[Andy Sturmer]].\n\nThough the characters speak English, the script intersperses their [[vernacular]] with [[Japanese language|Japanese]] speech, especially when the characters react to events that they find to be surprising. Calling out \"Tasukete!\" instead of \"Help!\" is commonly used.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:HHPAY Girls Rock!.jpg|220px|thumb|right|A picture of Ami and Yumi, titled \"Girls Rock!\", is done by [[Lynne Naylor]], one of the show's character designers back in 2005.]]\nAccording to Register, the target audience of the show is boys and girls from 6\u201311 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=6 |title=Interview with Sam Register: Page 6 |accessdate=June 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615124038/http://animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=6 |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref> However, it also has a [[cult following]] of teen and adult fans of the real-life [[Ami Onuki]] and [[Yumi Yoshimura]] who make up the Japanese [[Pop music|pop]] duo [[Puffy AmiYumi]]. Register, who was a fan of the band, wished to spread its fame to other parts of the world and thus created the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=4 |title=Interview with Sam Register: Page 4 |accessdate=June 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615124004/http://animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=4 |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe series features the adventures of animated versions of the duo, who have been immensely popular in Japan since making their debut in 1996. The group now has its own U.S. albums, including a 2004 companion album to this program, and was known to viewers of Cartoon Network in the USA for performing the theme to the [[Teen Titans (TV series)|''Teen Titans'' animated series]]. During production of the series, DeLisle learned some Japanese from Kawaye and Young, both of whom speak the language fluently.\n\nThe cartoon was one of the few cartoons at the time produced entirely in the United States (thus making their choice of characters quite ironic), with a number of characters designed by famed Canadian artist [[Lynne Naylor]] which got the show nominated for the coveted Annie Award. It used a combination of [[Macromedia Flash]] and traditional [[cel animation]].<ref>See boards drawings on [http://puffycrew.blogspot.com Puffy Crew Blog].</ref> Each program was 30 minutes long (with commercials) and featured three seven-minute segments. The visual style of the show is [[anime-influenced animation|anime-influenced]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/cartoon-network-turning-japanese-with-hi-hi-puffy-amiyumi/ |title=Cartoon Network Turning Japanese with Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi |date=October 7, 2017 |accessdate=November 19, 2004 |publisher=[[Animation Magazine]] }}</ref> The show takes inspiration from various works animated in Japan, such as ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'', ''[[ThunderCats (1985 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'', and the [[Sunbow Entertainment|Sunbow Productions]] animated series based on [[Hasbro]] properties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web-japan.org/kidsweb/archives/cool/05-03/puffy.html|title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi - What's Cool in Japan|publisher=Web Japan|date=March 2005|accessdate=June 13, 2009}}</ref> Other inspirations included old [[MGM]] and [[Warner Bros.]] cartoons, as well as [[Hanna-Barbera]] cartoons, [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]] shorts, and the works of [[Jay Ward]].\n\nSome of the show's crew members included various writers from [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[CatDog]]'', including [[Steven Banks]], Kit Boyce and Robert Lamoreaux.\n\n[[Sam Register]] originally pitched the idea of [[Puffy AmiYumi]] having their own television series on [[Cartoon Network]] and afterwards [[Renegade Animation]] developed a test short on April 22, 2003 in hopes of making the channel greenlight the show's production. Renegade Animation originally, at first, created other Cartoon Network pilots before ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi''; two of which feature ''Captain Sturdy''; one in 2001, entitled \"Back in Action\", and the other in 2003, entitled \"The Originals\", but they were ultimately rejected, and Renegade Animation then started working on ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' starting with its pilot on April 22, 2003. The pilot was not broadcast, but was initially successful, and got the green-light from Cartoon Network. Finally, it was shown in non-full version as a preview on Cartoon Network DVDs and VHS tapes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_6f-12EfUcA |title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi Pilot Promo - YouTube |publisher=youtube.com|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> The entire pilot was found by series' director, [[Darrell Van Citters]], and was uploaded to Vimeo on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lostmediawiki.com/Hi_Hi_Puffy_AmiYumi_(found_unaired_pilot_of_Cartoon_Network_animated_series;_2003) |title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi - Unaired Pilot - Lost Media Page |publisher=lostmediawiki.com|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/263460712 |title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi - Full Unaired Pilot - Vimeo |publisher=vimeo.com|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe series was officially announced at Cartoon Network's upfront on February 26, 2004. It was originally planned to premiere in December 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2004/cartoon-network-unveils-new-shows/|title=Cartoon Network Unveils New Shows|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref> but was later pushed back to November 19.<ref name=\"cnusa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icv2.com/articles/home/5781.html|title=Cartoon Network Offers J-Pop Hybrid|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Cancellation==\nOn October 2, 2006, the show's crew announced on their blog (puffycrew.blogspot.com) that Cartoon Network had cancelled ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' after three seasons and 39 episodes due to management shakeup, leading Sam Register to leave the channel. Afterwards, the network removed all mention of the series from its website.\n\nCartoon Network didn't acknowledge the series again until 2012, when Ami and Yumi appeared on the channel's 20th anniversary poster.<ref>[http://asset-2.soup.io/asset/4290/2953_25d1.jpeg Cartoon Network's 20th Anniversary Poster With Ami And Yumi]</ref>\n\nYumi later made a [[cameo appearance]] in the ''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]'' special ''Crossover Nexus''.\n\nAmi later made a [[cameo appearance]] in the ''[[Euro 2021]]'' opening ceremony at the Europe\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi episodes}}\n{{:List of Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi episodes}}\n\n''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' premiered in the United States on [[Cartoon Network]] on November 19, 2004.<ref name=\"cnusa\"/> After ending on June 27, 2006, the show continued to rerun until December 22, 2006, where it aired in reruns normally, and occasionally, would be one of the few non-[[Cartoon Cartoons]] to air in reruns on ''The Cartoon Cartoon Show'' before being removed from the network's schedule.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140808191003/http://www.tvschedulearchive.com/</ref>\n\nSince Cartoon Network is available worldwide, the show has been dubbed into multiple languages and aired on Cartoon Network worldwide. In Canada, the series premiered on [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] on September 5, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediaincanada.com/2005/08/16/yumi-20050816/|title=Yummy Tumi for YTV|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref> In Japan, the show began airing on Cartoon Network in English with Japanese [[subtitle (captioning)|subtitles]] in 2005. A dubbed version began airing on [[TV Tokyo]]'s [[Oha Suta]] block on October 6, 2005, and started to air on January 8, 2006 on [[Cartoon Network (Japan)|Cartoon Network Japan]].\n\nIn Germany, the show aired on [[Cartoon Network (Germany)|Cartoon Network Germany]] with all episodes. It premiered in 2005 on the Cartoon Network's block of [[Kabel eins]]. The show stopped airing there after two seasons in 2006. The reason was that [[Cartoon Network Germany]] launched and most of the shows moved there.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn Australia, the show premiered on the April 3, 2005.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20050403235646/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com.au/asp/tv/default.asp</ref> It stopped airing on [[Cartoon Network Australia]] in November 2008. The third season was never shown there. From August to November 2009, the Australian channel [[9Go!]] showed the last season instead and was abandoned in January 2010.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n[[Los Angeles Times]] wrote that the show is \"modern, in its retro, Asian-tinged way -- in other words, right in line with the Cartoon Network aesthetic -- but nothing new\", and called it \"bright and loud and sensational\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-nov-19-et-puffy19-story.html |title=\u2018Hi Hi Puffy\u2019 ready to rock |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=2004-11-19 |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' debuted on [[Cartoon Network]] on November 19, 2004 at 7:30 PM ET/PT with two half-hour episodes. The show charted double-digit increases with Girls 6\u201311 in ratings and delivery for Cartoon Network's Fridays programming block.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adgbc.com/bbs/showthread.php?t=6889|title=\"Puffy AmiYumi Show\" Ratings Release|accessdate=September 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140918052850/http://www.adgbc.com/bbs/showthread.php?t=6889|archive-date=2014-09-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the following week, the show became the network's top-rated hit for kids 6\u201311. It also increased Cartoon Network's audience among that age group by 49% over the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/licensing/mattel-to-license-hi-hi-puffy-ami-yumi/|title=Mattel to License Hi Hi Puffy Ami Yumi|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nThe series has been nominated three times for the [[Annie Award]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://imdb.com/title/tt0407398/awards | title= Awards for \"Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi\" | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=2006-08-28}}</ref> Two of them came in 2005 and one came in 2006.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Result\n! Award\n! Category\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2005\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Nominated\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Annie\n| Character Design in an Animated Television Production for Shakeh Haghnazarian and Lynne Naylor\n|-\n| Production Design in an Animated Television Production for Michael Giaimo (for first episode)\n|-\n| 2006\n| Best Production Design in an Animated Television Production for Michael Giaimo\n|}\n\n==Merchandise==\n\n===CD===\n* ''[[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi (album)|Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi]]''\n* ''[[Hi Hi (Puffy AmiYumi)|Hi Hi]]''\n\n===DVD releases===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 rowspan=2|Season\n! rowspan=2|Episodes\n! Release dates\n! rowspan=2|Special Features\n|-\n! [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#8888FF|\n| 1\n| rowspan=2|13\n| style=\"font-size:90%\"|'''''Volume 1: Let's Go!''''': November 29, 2005<br />'''Episodes''': 1 (\"Dis-Harmony\" / \"Collect All 5\" / \"Ninjcompoop\"), 3 (\"Ami's Secret\" / \"Taffy Trouble\" / \"Dance a Go-Go\"), 11 (\"The Amazing Kaz-Am\" / \"Puffylicious\" / \"Lights Camera Danger\") and 12 (\"Fan Clubs\" / \"Cat Nap\" / \"Cursed!\")<hr />'''''Volume 2: Rock Forever''''': November 29, 2005<br />'''Episodes''': 5 (\"Showdown!\" / \"In the Cards\" / \"Team Teen\") and 9 (\"Yumi Saves Kaz\" / \"Rock 'N Roe\" / \"Scowlitis\")\n| Dance A Go-Go Totally Trivial Trivia Track<br />Backstage with Puffy AmiYumi\n|-\n| style=\"background:#5BE85B|\n| 2\n| style=\"font-size:90%\"|'''''Volume 2: Rock Forever''''': November 29, 2005<br />'''Episodes''': 14 (\"Koi Fish\" / \"Arbor Day\" / \"Ami Ami\") and 16 (\"Hungry Yumi\" / \"The Oddyguard\" / \"Song Sung Bad\")\n| Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi Music Video (including Karaoke style)<br />Speak Japanese with Puffy AmiYumi\n|}\n\n===Video games===\nThere are two video games released by [[D3 Publisher|D3Publisher of America (D3PA)]] based on the show.\n* ''[[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi: Kaznapped!]]'' ([[Game Boy Advance]]) (2005)\n* ''[[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi: The Genie and the Amp]]'' ([[Nintendo DS]]) (2006)\n\n===Marketing===\n* A \"falloon\" (a float with balloon elements) of Puffy AmiYumi's cartoon tour bus (complete with the supporting characters in puppet form), the cartoon version of Puffy AmiYumi as a balloon, and the real PUFFY appeared in the [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.warnermediagroup.com/newsroom/press-releases/2005/10/31/cartoon-network-unveils-hi-hi-puffy-amiyumi-float-for-the-79th|title= Cartoon Network Unveils Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi Float For the 79th Annual Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade\u00ae|date= 31 October 2005|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180831123844/https://www.warnermediagroup.com/newsroom/press-releases/2005/10/31/cartoon-network-unveils-hi-hi-puffy-amiyumi-float-for-the-79th|publisher= WarnerMedia|archive-date= 2018-08-31|access-date= 31 August 2018|url-status= live}}</ref> A video of this Macy Parade Float in Chicago can be viewed on [http://sumo.tv/video/324854 SUMO.tv]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\n* A line of toys intended for girls was produced by [[Mattel]] (makers of the popular [[Barbie]] doll and [[Hot Wheels]] cars) and released for the 2005 Christmas season.\n* Two DVDs, ''Let's Go!'' and ''Rock Forever'', featuring various episodes of the show, were released on November 29, 2005.\n* The American costume company Rubie's produced a line of ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' costumes and accessories for girls for [[Halloween]] 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rubies.com/landingpage.cfm?ItemNumber=882325 |title=Yumi |publisher=Rubie's |accessdate=2006-08-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930003543/http://www.rubies.com/landingpage.cfm?ItemNumber=882325 |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rubies.com/landingpage.cfm?ItemNumber=882323 |title=Ami |publisher=Rubie's |accessdate=2006-08-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930003537/http://www.rubies.com/landingpage.cfm?ItemNumber=882323 |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television|United States|Cartoon}}\n* [[PUFFY]]\n* [[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi: The Genie and the Amp]] ([[Nintendo DS]]) (2006)\n* [[Pink Lady and Jeff]], the previous attempt to import a Japanese pop group to US television.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060111031915/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/puffyamiyumi/ Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi] at ''[[Cartoon Network]]''\n* {{IMDb title|0407398}}\n* {{tv.com show|hi-hi-puffy-amiyumi}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi}}\n{{Puffy AmiYumi}}\n{{Cartoon Network original programming}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi| ]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2004 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animated television series]]\n[[Category:Metafictional television series]]\n[[Category:Puffy AmiYumi]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Sam Register]]\n[[Category:Radio Philippines Network shows]]\n[[Category:Television series based on singers and musicians]]\n[[Category:American television series with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Japan]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Animated duos]]\n[[Category:Animated musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American-Japanese television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi\n| image                    = Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi.svg\n| image_size               = 220px\n| genre                    = <!--Must be sourced per Template:Infobox television-->\n| creator                  = Sam Register\n| director                 = {{unbulleted list|Darin McGowan|Howie Perry|Scott O'Brien|[[Darrell Van Citters]] <small>(supervising director)</small>}}\n| starring                 = {{unbulleted list|[[Ami Onuki]]|[[Yumi Yoshimura]]}}\n| voices                   = {{unbulleted list|[[Janice Kawaye]]|[[Grey DeLisle]]|[[Keone Young]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Puffy AmiYumi]]<br />[[Andy Sturmer]]\n| opentheme                = \"[[Hi Hi (Puffy AmiYumi)|Hi Hi]]\"<br /><small>performed by [[Puffy AmiYumi]]</small>\n| endtheme                 = \"Hi Hi\" <small>(Instrumental)</small>\n| composer                 = {{unbulleted list|Puffy AmiYumi <small>(original songs)</small>|[[Andy Sturmer]]}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| network                  = [[Cartoon Network]]\n| executive_producer       = Sam Register<br />Tramm Wigzell\n| producer                 = Ashley Postlewaite\n| editor                   = {{unbulleted list|Thom Whitehead <br /><small>(Season 1)</small>|Joe Campana|Nate Pacheco <small>(Season 1\u20132)</small>|Michael D'Ambrosio|Rick Greenwald <br /><small>(Season 2\u20133)</small>|Michelle Wong <br /><small>(Season 4)}}\n| company                  = [[Renegade Animation]]<br />[[Cartoon Network Studios]]\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| num_seasons              = 3\n| num_episodes             = 39 (117 segments and 1 pilot)\n| list_episodes            = List of Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi episodes\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_run                = April 22, 2003 {{small|(pilot)}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2004|11|19}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2006|6|27}}\n| website                  = \n}}\n'''''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi''''' is an American animated television series created by [[Sam Register]] for [[Cartoon Network]].<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=284-285}}</ref> Produced by [[Renegade Animation]] and [[Cartoon Network Studios]], the series stars fictionalized and animated versions of the [[Music of Japan|Japanese]] [[pop rock]] group [[Puffy AmiYumi]]. The series premiered on November 19, 2004 and ended on June 27, 2006 with a total of three seasons and 39 episodes, leaving a total of 34 episodes aired and five episodes unaired in North America.\n\nDuring its run, the series has been nominated for an [[Annie Award]] three times. The series has developed a strong [[cult following]]. Merchandise based on the series has also been produced during its run, such as video games, home media releases, toys, and clothing.\n\n==Premise==\n[[File:Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi Characters.png|220px|thumb|left|The main cast of the show. From left to right: Ami, Kaz, Yumi, Jang-Keng, and Tekirai.]]\n''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' follows the adventures of two [[pop stars]] and best friends: [[Yumi Yoshimura]] ([[Grey DeLisle]]), a cynical, sarcastic, rough and tough [[punk rock]]er; and [[Ami Onuki]] ([[Janice Kawaye]]), a peppy, optimistic and cute schoolgirl. Both are based off the real Japanese [[Pop music|pop]] duo [[Puffy AmiYumi]], but with different appearances and exaggerated personalities. They travel around the world on their customized tour bus along with their well-intentioned yet greedy manager Kaz Harada ([[Keone Young]]). From rocking out at a concert to hanging out in their hometown of [[Tokyo, Japan|Tokyo]], the duo take the world by storm with their musical talent, trend-setting style, and humor, dishing out lessons in J-pop justice and establishing the international language of \"cool\" along the way.\n\nSecondary characters include: Jang-Keng (Grey DeLisle) and Tekirai (Janice Kawaye), the duo's pet cats who enjoy tormenting Kaz; Harmony ([[Sandy Fox]]), a six-year-old girl who is the self-proclaimed \"Number One Fan\" of Puffy AmiYumi and (later) Kaz and constantly stalks them; Eldwin Blair (Nathan Carlson), a sinister land developer who tries to tear down beloved places for his own selfish needs; King Chad ([[Katie Leigh]]), a selfish \"bad boy\" who is a master of the card game ''Stu-Pi-Doh!'' (a parody of ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh!]]''); the evil Talent Suckers (Nathan Carlson; [[Corey Burton]]), a [[vampire]] rock trio from [[Transylvania]]; and Atchan ([[Rob Paulsen]]), a caricature of Vo Atsushi (lead singer of the [[Pop music|pop]] band New Rote'ka) who speaks in third-person and thinks he is a superhero.\n\nThe animated Puffy AmiYumi travel all over the world in their tour bus. While appearing the same size as a regular bus on the outside, it appears to have enough internal space to house the girls' rooms (including full-sized beds), Kaz's room, their equipment, televisions, and computers, among other things. In the episode \"Domo\", Kaz refers to an upstairs area. It also seems capable of running on autopilot, as Kaz, Ami, and Yumi are sometimes sitting in the rear cabin of the bus while traveling. Occasionally, the rear door has been opened to receive packages delivered by a boy on a scooter.\n\nDuring the first season, the show included [[live-action]] clips of the real Ami and Yumi making childish commentary (in English and non-subtitled Japanese) at the beginning and end of each episode. They only performed short clips at the beginning of the show during the second and third seasons. Starting with the second season, the duo was sometimes shown holding title cards introducing the cartoon segments. At the end of the episode \"Sitcomi Yumi\", Ami and Yumi watched television and saw the animated Kaz with the real Ami and Yumi. All of the live-action clips were produced by Freegate, Ltd.\n\nThe real PUFFY performs the cartoon's theme song (which is also in Japanese, German, European French, Canadian French, Castilian Spanish, Latin American Spanish, Danish, Norwegian, Polish, Chinese, Taiwanese Mandarin, Dutch, Arabic, Hebrew, Turkish, Brazilian Portuguese and European Portuguese in the respective regions), and many episodes feature one or more of the duo's songs playing in the background, along with music by [[Andy Sturmer]].\n\nThough the characters speak English, the script intersperses their [[vernacular]] with [[Japanese language|Japanese]] speech, especially when the characters react to events that they find to be surprising. Calling out \"Tasukete!\" instead of \"Help!\" is commonly used.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:HHPAY Girls Rock!.jpg|220px|thumb|right|A picture of Ami and Yumi, titled \"Girls Rock!\", is done by [[Lynne Naylor]], one of the show's character designers back in 2005.]]\nAccording to Register, the target audience of the show is boys and girls from 6\u201311 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=6 |title=Interview with Sam Register: Page 6 |accessdate=June 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615124038/http://animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=6 |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref> However, it also has a [[cult following]] of teen and adult fans of the real-life [[Ami Onuki]] and [[Yumi Yoshimura]] who make up the Japanese [[Pop music|pop]] duo [[Puffy AmiYumi]]. Register, who was a fan of the band, wished to spread its fame to other parts of the world and thus created the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=4 |title=Interview with Sam Register: Page 4 |accessdate=June 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615124004/http://animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=76&document=4 |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe series features the adventures of animated versions of the duo, who have been immensely popular in Japan since making their debut in 1996. The group now has its own U.S. albums, including a 2004 companion album to this program, and was known to viewers of Cartoon Network in the USA for performing the theme to the [[Teen Titans (TV series)|''Teen Titans'' animated series]]. During production of the series, DeLisle learned some Japanese from Kawaye and Young, both of whom speak the language fluently.\n\nThe cartoon was one of the few cartoons at the time produced entirely in the United States (thus making their choice of characters quite ironic), with a number of characters designed by famed Canadian artist [[Lynne Naylor]] which got the show nominated for the coveted Annie Award. It used a combination of [[Macromedia Flash]] and traditional [[cel animation]].<ref>See boards drawings on [http://puffycrew.blogspot.com Puffy Crew Blog].</ref> Each program was 30 minutes long (with commercials) and featured three seven-minute segments. The visual style of the show is [[anime-influenced animation|anime-influenced]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/cartoon-network-turning-japanese-with-hi-hi-puffy-amiyumi/ |title=Cartoon Network Turning Japanese with Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi |date=October 7, 2017 |accessdate=November 19, 2004 |publisher=[[Animation Magazine]] }}</ref> The show takes inspiration from various works animated in Japan, such as ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'', ''[[ThunderCats (1985 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'', and the [[Sunbow Entertainment|Sunbow Productions]] animated series based on [[Hasbro]] properties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web-japan.org/kidsweb/archives/cool/05-03/puffy.html|title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi - What's Cool in Japan|publisher=Web Japan|date=March 2005|accessdate=June 13, 2009}}</ref> Other inspirations included old [[MGM]] and [[Warner Bros.]] cartoons, as well as [[Hanna-Barbera]] cartoons, [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]] shorts, and the works of [[Jay Ward]].\n\nSome of the show's crew members included various writers from [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[CatDog]]'', including [[Steven Banks]], Kit Boyce and Robert Lamoreaux.\n\n[[Sam Register]] originally pitched the idea of [[Puffy AmiYumi]] having their own television series on [[Cartoon Network]] and afterwards [[Renegade Animation]] developed a test short on April 22, 2003 in hopes of making the channel greenlight the show's production. Renegade Animation originally, at first, created other Cartoon Network pilots before ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi''; two of which feature ''Captain Sturdy''; one in 2001, entitled \"Back in Action\", and the other in 2003, entitled \"The Originals\", but they were ultimately rejected, and Renegade Animation then started working on ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' starting with its pilot on April 22, 2003. The pilot was not broadcast, but was initially successful, and got the green-light from Cartoon Network. Finally, it was shown in non-full version as a preview on Cartoon Network DVDs and VHS tapes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_6f-12EfUcA |title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi Pilot Promo - YouTube |publisher=youtube.com|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> The entire pilot was found by series' director, [[Darrell Van Citters]], and was uploaded to Vimeo on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lostmediawiki.com/Hi_Hi_Puffy_AmiYumi_(found_unaired_pilot_of_Cartoon_Network_animated_series;_2003) |title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi - Unaired Pilot - Lost Media Page |publisher=lostmediawiki.com|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/263460712 |title=Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi - Full Unaired Pilot - Vimeo |publisher=vimeo.com|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe series was officially announced at Cartoon Network's upfront on February 26, 2004. It was originally planned to premiere in December 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2004/cartoon-network-unveils-new-shows/|title=Cartoon Network Unveils New Shows|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref> but was later pushed back to November 19.<ref name=\"cnusa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icv2.com/articles/home/5781.html|title=Cartoon Network Offers J-Pop Hybrid|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Cancellation==\nOn October 2, 2006, the show's crew announced on their blog (puffycrew.blogspot.com) that Cartoon Network had cancelled ''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' after three seasons and 39 episodes due to management shakeup, leading Sam Register to leave the channel. Afterwards, the network removed all mention of the series from its website.\n\nCartoon Network didn't acknowledge the series again until 2012, when Ami and Yumi appeared on the channel's 20th anniversary poster.<ref>[http://asset-2.soup.io/asset/4290/2953_25d1.jpeg Cartoon Network's 20th Anniversary Poster With Ami And Yumi]</ref>\n\nYumi later made a [[cameo appearance]] in the ''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]'' special ''Crossover Nexus''.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi episodes}}\n{{:List of Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi episodes}}\n\n''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' premiered in the United States on [[Cartoon Network]] on November 19, 2004.<ref name=\"cnusa\"/> After ending on June 27, 2006, the show continued to rerun until December 22, 2006, where it aired in reruns normally, and occasionally, would be one of the few non-[[Cartoon Cartoons]] to air in reruns on ''The Cartoon Cartoon Show'' before being removed from the network's schedule.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20140808191003/http://www.tvschedulearchive.com/</ref>\n\nSince Cartoon Network is available worldwide, the show has been dubbed into multiple languages and aired on Cartoon Network worldwide. In Canada, the series premiered on [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] on September 5, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediaincanada.com/2005/08/16/yumi-20050816/|title=Yummy Tumi for YTV|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref> In Japan, the show began airing on Cartoon Network in English with Japanese [[subtitle (captioning)|subtitles]] in 2005. A dubbed version began airing on [[TV Tokyo]]'s [[Oha Suta]] block on October 6, 2005, and started to air on January 8, 2006 on [[Cartoon Network (Japan)|Cartoon Network Japan]].\n\nIn Germany, the show aired on [[Cartoon Network (Germany)|Cartoon Network Germany]] with all episodes. It premiered in 2005 on the Cartoon Network's block of [[Kabel eins]]. The show stopped airing there after two seasons in 2006. The reason was that [[Cartoon Network Germany]] launched and most of the shows moved there.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn Australia, the show premiered on the April 3, 2005.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20050403235646/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com.au/asp/tv/default.asp</ref> It stopped airing on [[Cartoon Network Australia]] in November 2008. The third season was never shown there. From August to November 2009, the Australian channel [[9Go!]] showed the last season instead and was abandoned in January 2010.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n[[Los Angeles Times]] wrote that the show is \"modern, in its retro, Asian-tinged way -- in other words, right in line with the Cartoon Network aesthetic -- but nothing new\", and called it \"bright and loud and sensational\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-nov-19-et-puffy19-story.html |title=\u2018Hi Hi Puffy\u2019 ready to rock |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=2004-11-19 |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n''Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi'' debuted on [[Cartoon Network]] on November 19, 2004 at 7:30 PM ET/PT with two half-hour episodes. The show charted double-digit increases with Girls 6\u201311 in ratings and delivery for Cartoon Network's Fridays programming block.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adgbc.com/bbs/showthread.php?t=6889|title=\"Puffy AmiYumi Show\" Ratings Release|accessdate=September 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140918052850/http://www.adgbc.com/bbs/showthread.php?t=6889|archive-date=2014-09-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the following week, the show became the network's top-rated hit for kids 6\u201311. It also increased Cartoon Network's audience among that age group by 49% over the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/licensing/mattel-to-license-hi-hi-puffy-ami-yumi/|title=Mattel to License Hi Hi Puffy Ami Yumi|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nThe series has been nominated three times for the [[Annie Award]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://imdb.com/title/tt0407398/awards | title= Awards for \"Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi\" | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=2006-08-28}}</ref> Two of them came in 2005 and one came in 2006.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Result\n! Award\n! Category\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2005\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Nominated\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Annie\n| Character Design in an Animated Television Production for Shakeh Haghnazarian and Lynne Naylor\n|-\n| Production Design in an Animated Television Production for Michael Giaimo (for first episode)\n|-\n| 2006\n| Best Production Design in an Animated Television Production for Michael Giaimo\n|}\n\n==Merchandise==\n\n===CD===\n* ''[[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi (album)|Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi]]''\n* ''[[Hi Hi (Puffy AmiYumi)|Hi Hi]]''\n\n===DVD releases===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 rowspan=2|Season\n! rowspan=2|Episodes\n! Release dates\n! rowspan=2|Special Features\n|-\n! [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#8888FF|\n| 1\n| rowspan=2|13\n| style=\"font-size:90%\"|'''''Volume 1: Let's Go!''''': November 29, 2005<br />'''Episodes''': 1 (\"Dis-Harmony\" / \"Collect All 5\" / \"Ninjcompoop\"), 3 (\"Ami's Secret\" / \"Taffy Trouble\" / \"Dance a Go-Go\"), 11 (\"The Amazing Kaz-Am\" / \"Puffylicious\" / \"Lights Camera Danger\") and 12 (\"Fan Clubs\" / \"Cat Nap\" / \"Cursed!\")<hr />'''''Volume 2: Rock Forever''''': November 29, 2005<br />'''Episodes''': 5 (\"Showdown!\" / \"In the Cards\" / \"Team Teen\") and 9 (\"Yumi Saves Kaz\" / \"Rock 'N Roe\" / \"Scowlitis\")\n| Dance A Go-Go Totally Trivial Trivia Track<br />Backstage with Puffy AmiYumi\n|-\n| style=\"background:#5BE85B|\n| 2\n| 