e a precise definition.\n\n==Related terms==\nBefore the financial crisis started, the term \"toxic waste\" was used to describe the lowest tranch of the subprime mortgage market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/blackburn03222007.html |title=Toxic waste in the sub-prime market| publisher=Counter Punch|accessdate=2009-03-22}}</ref>  \"Legacy assets\" is a [[euphemism]] coined by [[Robert Gibbs]] as an attempted re-branding of toxic assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/potus-notes/2009/Mar/23/geithner-rebrands-toxic-assets-as-legacy-loans/ |title=TGeithner rebrands toxic assets as \"legacy loans\"| publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=2009-10-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Toxic security''' is the name applied during the aftermath of the [[Subprime mortgage crisis|subprime meltdown]] to financial instruments which cannot be readily identified as an asset or a liability.  According to [[George Soros]], \"the toxic securities in question are not homogeneous\".<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d68e10cc-8f45-11dd-946c-0000779fd18c.html Recapitalise the banking system - FT.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  One example would be a [[credit default swap]] that entitles the holder to a regular stream of small payments but obliges the holder to make a large payment if a specified event occurs.  John Gapper describes one such instrument, a \"tail risk\" swap:\n<blockquote>\n''...[S]tructured finance gave banks and others more chances to take on \u201ctail risk\u201d. This is an insurance-like trading strategy: one institution writes swaps or options that provide it with regular payments in exchange for taking another\u2019s risk of default. In most cases, this produces profits, but occasionally it is disastrous.''<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5fdd7bd8-866d-11dd-959e-0000779fd18c.html King\u2019s men must put themselves together again - FT.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe right to receive a stream of payments is